# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: defold-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:defold-engine/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:defold-engine/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:defold-engine/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold is a downloadable desktop app, and ships with its own embedded IDE.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold targets desktop, mobile, web, and console platforms.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold is free-to-use and is source-available.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold has over 30,000 users, and has been used to publish over 100 games.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Exported games with Defold typically use less than 100kB RAM and very small bundle sizes, less than 2 MB, due to the Engine's modularization and efficient core.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold uses Lua for scripting, but also allows native extensions, written in C, C++, and target-specific native languages.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold projects are organized as collections, which consist of a hierarchy of game objects containing in-game entities.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Scripting between game objects is handled using the message-passing paradigm, which allows scripts to intercommunicate in call-response and event-based models.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold's IDE natively supports in-editor Git tracking.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The Defold editor can be run on three platforms and natively supports targeting eight platforms.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Users communicate with the engine via a Lua API.
[src:defold-engine/defold] LuaJIT is used on all platforms except HTML and just-in-time compilation is enabled on permitted platforms.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Users can extend the engine using C, C++, Java, Objective-C, and JavaScript for platform-specific or more performant code.
[src:defold-engine/defold] In addition, the community maintains TypeScript and Haxe bindings.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The editor includes a visual scene editor, debugger, asset management, tilemap editor, and all templates required for bundling the game.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Newer versions support hot-reloading, to make changes to assets and scripts without rebuilding the project.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The render pipeline can be customized via a render script API, which can be translated into OpenGL, OpenGL ES, Vulkan, or Metal (via MoltenVK) depending on the user's needs.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Shaders can be written in GLSL for various post-processing effects.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold has support for extensions, which are plugins that extend the engine, where users can integrate auxiliary solutions into their projects.
[src:defold-engine/defold] There are libraries for simplifying game systems, interacting with hardware, and integration with third-party software.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Both the Defold Foundation and the community host their extensions on the Defold Asset Portal.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold was created in 2008 by Christian Murray and Ragnar Svensson As a side-project while they were working at Avalanche Studios, and later as a full time business before being acquired by King in 2014.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold was developed and used internally at King for a few years before the decision was made to make Defold available to developers outside of King.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The announcement and release of Defold as a free to use game engine was made at the Game Developers Conference in San Francisco in March 2016.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Some mobile developers expressed concern about King's long term intentions for the engine, as well as the lack of a clear business goal.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Development has continued with bi-weekly incremental releases of the engine and editor, with a major milestone being the release of the new editor in 2017.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold was nominated for best engine in the 2018 Develop Awards, the 2018 and 2019 Mobile Games Awards.
[src:defold-engine/defold] In 2020, the Defold Foundation was established to oversee the development and stewardship of the engine, ensuring its independence from any single entity.
[src:defold-engine/defold] In the process, the source code for the engine was made public.
[src:defold-engine/defold] King released the source on GitHub as open source game engine, but community of developers questioned the choice of license, as it was initially unclear.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Many assumed it was released under an Apache 2.0 - popular open source license.
[src:defold-engine/defold] However, King had used a custom license that prevented commercialization of the Defold editor, so that Defold would always remain free for developers to use, calling into question whether it could be considered open source as defined by the Free Software Foundation and the Open Source Initiative.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Shortly after, Defold added support for Nintendo Switch target platform exports.
[src:defold-engine/defold] Defold is released under the "Defold License" which is derived from the permissive Apache License, Version 2.0.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The engine is "source available" and developers can access the engine's source code on GitHub.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The "Defold License" license permits any use of the code except for the sale of the Defold engine itself.
[src:defold-engine/defold] However, games made with the Defold Engine are unaffected and can be distributed freely without restriction or royalties.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The Defold Foundation is funded entirely by community donations and corporate partnerships.
[src:defold-engine/defold] The Defold engine is maintained by both the Defold foundation and open source developers.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:defold-engine/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua originated in 1993 as a language for extending software applications to meet the increasing demand for customization at the time.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] It provided the basic facilities of most procedural programming languages, but more complicated or domain-specific features were not included; rather, it included mechanisms for extending the language, allowing programmers to implement such features.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] As Lua was intended to be a general embeddable extension language, the designers of Lua focused on improving its speed, portability, extensibility and ease-of-use in development.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua was created in 1993 by Roberto Ierusalimschy, Luiz Henrique de Figueiredo, and Waldemar Celes, members of the Computer Graphics Technology Group (Tecgraf) at the Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro, in Brazil.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] From 1977 until 1992, Brazil had a policy of strong trade barriers (called a market reserve) for computer hardware and software, believing that Brazil could and should produce its own hardware and software.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In that climate, Tecgraf's clients could not afford, either politically or financially, to buy customized software from abroad; under the market reserve, clients would have to go through a complex bureaucratic process to prove their needs couldn't be met by Brazilian companies.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Those reasons led Tecgraf to implement the basic tools it needed from scratch.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua's predecessors were the data-description and configuration languages Simple Object Language (SOL) and Data-Entry Language (DEL).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] They had been independently developed at Tecgraf in 1992–1993 to add some flexibility into two different projects (both were interactive graphical programs for engineering applications at Petrobras company).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] There was a lack of any flow-control structures in SOL and DEL, and Petrobras felt a growing need to add full programming power to them.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua 1.0 was designed in such a way that its object constructors, being then slightly different from the current light and flexible style, incorporated the data-description syntax of SOL (hence the name Lua: *Sol* meaning "Sun" in Portuguese, and *Lua* meaning "Moon").
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Dobb's Journal*, Lua's creators also state that LISP and Scheme with their single, ubiquitous data-structure mechanism (the list) were a major influence on their decision to develop the table as the primary data structure of Lua.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua semantics have been increasingly influenced by Scheme over time, especially with the introduction of anonymous functions and full lexical scoping.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Several features were added in new Lua versions.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Versions of Lua prior to version 5.0 were released under a license similar to the BSD license.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] From version 5.0 onwards, Lua has been licensed under the MIT License.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Both are permissive free software licences and are almost identical.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua is commonly described as a "multi-paradigm" language, providing a small set of general features that can be extended to fit different problem types.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua does not contain explicit support for inheritance, but allows it to be implemented with metatables.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In general, Lua strives to provide simple, flexible meta-features that can be extended as needed, rather than supply a feature-set specific to one programming paradigm.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] As a result, the base language is light; the full reference interpreter is only about 293 kB compiled and easily adaptable to a broad range of applications.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] As a dynamically typed language intended for use as an extension language or scripting language, Lua is compact enough to fit on a variety of host platforms.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] It supports only a small number of atomic data structures such as Boolean values, numbers (double-precision floating point and 64-bit integers by default) and strings.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Typical data structures such as arrays, sets, lists and records can be represented using Lua's single native data structure, the table, which is essentially a heterogeneous associative array.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua implements a small set of advanced features such as first-class functions, garbage collection, closures, proper tail calls, coercion (automatic conversion between string and number values at run time), coroutines (cooperative multitasking) and dynamic module loading.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The declaration of a variable, without a value.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A comment in Lua starts with a double-hyphen and runs to the end of the line, similar to Ada, Eiffel, Haskell, SQL and VHDL.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Multi-line strings and comments are marked with double square brackets.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua has one type of conditional test: `if then end` with optional `else` and `elseif then` execution control constructs.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua has four types of conditional loops: the `while` loop, the `repeat` loop (similar to a `do while` loop), the numeric `for` loop and the generic `for` loop.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Loops can also be nested (put inside of another loop).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Any future calls to `print` will now be routed through the new function, and because of Lua's lexical scoping, the old print function will only be accessible by the new, modified print.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A new closure for the variable `x` is created every time `addto` is called, so that each new anonymous function returned will always access its own `x` parameter.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The closure is managed by Lua's garbage collector, just like any other object.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Tables are the most important data structures (and, by design, the only built-in composite data type) in Lua and are the foundation of all user-created types.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] They are associative arrays with addition of automatic numeric key and special syntax.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A table is a set of key and data pairs, where the data is referenced by key; in other words, it is a hashed heterogeneous associative array.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Tables are created using the `{}` constructor syntax.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Tables are always passed by reference (see Call by sharing).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A key (index) can be any value except `nil` and NaN, including functions.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A table is often used as structure (or record) by using strings as keys.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Because such use is very common, Lua features a special syntax for accessing such fields.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] By using a table to store related functions, it can act as a namespace.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Tables are automatically assigned a numerical key, enabling them to be used as an array data type.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The first automatic index is 1 rather than 0 as it is for many other programming languages (though an explicit index of 0 is allowed).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A numeric key `1` is distinct from a string key `"1"`.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The length of a table `t` is defined to be any integer index `n` such that `t[n]` is not `nil` and `t[n+1]` is `nil`; moreover, if `t[1]` is `nil`, `n` can be zero.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] For a regular array, with non-nil values from 1 to a given `n`, its length is exactly that `n`, the index of its last value.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] If the array has "holes" (that is, nil values between other non-nil values), then `#t` can be any of the indices that directly precedes a `nil` value (that is, it may consider any such nil value as the end of the array).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Using a hash map to emulate an array is normally slower than using an actual array; however, Lua tables are optimized for use as arrays to help avoid this issue.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Extensible semantics is a key feature of Lua, and the metatable allows powerful customization of tables.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The following example demonstrates an "infinite" table.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] For any `n`, `fibs[n]` will give the `n`-th Fibonacci number using dynamic programming and memoization.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Although Lua does not have a built-in concept of classes, object-oriented programming can be emulated using functions and tables.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] An object is formed by putting methods and fields in a table.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Inheritance (both single and multiple) can be implemented with metatables, delegating nonexistent methods and fields to a parent object.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] There is no such concept as "class" with these techniques; rather, prototypes are used, similar to Self or JavaScript.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] New objects are created either with a factory method (that constructs new objects from scratch) or by cloning an existing object.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Here, `setmetatable` tells Lua to look for an element in the `Vector` table if it is not present in the `vec` table.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] `vec.magnitude`, which is equivalent to `vec["magnitude"]`, first looks in the `vec` table for the `magnitude` element.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The `vec` table does not have a `magnitude` element, but its metatable delegates to the `Vector` table for the `magnitude` element when it's not found in the `vec` table.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua provides some syntactic sugar to facilitate object orientation.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] To declare member functions inside a prototype table, one can use `function table:func(args)`, which is equivalent to `function table.func(self, args)`.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Calling class methods also makes use of the colon: `object:func(args)` is equivalent to `object.func(object, args)`.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] It is possible to use metatables to mimic the behavior of class inheritance in Lua.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In this example, we allow vectors to have their values multiplied by a constant in a derived class.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] It is also possible to implement multiple inheritance; `__index` can either be a function or a table.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Operator overloading can also be done; Lua metatables can have elements such as `__add`, `__sub` and so on.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua programs are not interpreted directly from the textual Lua file, but are compiled into bytecode, which is then run on the Lua virtual machine (VM).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The compiling process is typically invisible to the user and is performed during run-time, especially when a just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler is used, but it can be done offline to increase loading performance or reduce the memory footprint of the host environment by leaving out the compiler.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua bytecode can also be produced and executed from within Lua, using the `dump` function from the string library and the `load/loadstring/loadfile` functions.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua version 5.5.0 is implemented in approximately 32,000 lines of C code.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Like most CPUs, and unlike most virtual machines (which are stack-based), the Lua VM is register-based, and therefore more closely resembles most hardware design.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The register architecture both avoids excessive copying of values, and reduces the total number of instructions per function.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The virtual machine of Lua 5 is one of the first register-based pure VMs to have a wide use.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Parrot and Android's Dalvik are two other well-known register-based VMs.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua is intended to be embedded into other applications, and provides a C API for this purpose.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The API is divided into two parts: the Lua core and the Lua auxiliary library.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The Lua API's design eliminates the need for manual reference counting (management) in C code, unlike Python's API.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The API, like the language, is minimalist.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Advanced functions are provided by the auxiliary library, which consists largely of preprocessor macros which assist with complex table operations.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua provides functions to push and pop most simple C data types (integers, floats, etc.) to and from the stack, and functions to manipulate tables through the stack.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The Lua stack is somewhat different from a traditional stack; the stack can be indexed directly, for example.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Negative indices indicate offsets from the top of the stack.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] For example, −1 is the top (most recently pushed value), while positive indices indicate offsets from the bottom (oldest value).
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Marshalling data between C and Lua functions is also done using the stack.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] To call a Lua function, arguments are pushed onto the stack, and then the `lua_call` is used to call the actual function.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] When writing a C function to be directly called from Lua, the arguments are read from the stack.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] The C API also provides some special tables, located at various "pseudo-indices" in the Lua stack.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] At `LUA_GLOBALSINDEX` prior to Lua 5.2 is the globals table, `_G` from within Lua, which is the main namespace.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] There is also a registry located at `LUA_REGISTRYINDEX` where C programs can store Lua values for later retrieval.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Besides standard library (core) modules it is possible to write extensions using the Lua API.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Extension modules are shared objects which can be used to extend the functions of the interpreter by providing native facilities to Lua scripts.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Lua scripts may load extension modules using `require`, just like modules written in Lua itself, or with `package.loadlib`.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] When a C library is loaded via `require('foo')` Lua will look for the function `luaopen_foo` and call it, which acts as any C function callable from Lua and generally returns a table filled with methods.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] A growing set of modules termed *rocks* are available through a package management system named LuaRocks, in the spirit of CPAN, RubyGems and Python eggs.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Prewritten Lua bindings exist for most popular programming languages, including other scripting languages.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] For C++, there are a number of template-based approaches and some automatic binding generators.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In video game development, Lua is widely used as a scripting language, mainly due to its perceived ease of embedding, fast execution, and short learning curve.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Notable games which use Lua include *Roblox*, *Garry's Mod*, *World of Warcraft*, *Payday 2*, *Project Zomboid*, *Phantasy Star Online 2*, *Dota 2*, *Crysis*, and many others.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] Also, Lua is used in non-video game software, such as Adobe Lightroom, Moho, iClone, Aerospike, and some system software in FreeBSD and NetBSD, and used as a template scripting language on MediaWiki using the Scribunto extension.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In 2003, a poll conducted by GameDev.net showed that Lua was the most popular scripting language for game programming.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] On 12 January 2012, Lua was announced as a winner of the Front Line Award 2011 from the magazine *Game Developer* in the category Programming Tools.
[src:defold-engine/lua-programming-language] In addition, the Lua users community provides some *power patches* on top of the reference C implementation.
